From Noel Rappin Subject Re Box score abbrev woes Scott Barman writes In article jay rogoff writes Can anybody figure out why some box score abbreviations make absolutely no sense At least in the local Gannett rag that finds its way to my I must have stared at Cleman in the Mets' box for a good seconds this morning wondering who the hell it Wouldn't it make more sense to use Colemn I've seen it as Colmn Blame the Associated After the official scorer balances the official score card they copy it and give it to several diffent One of those is a person from AP whose job it is to type it up using a template on a laptop and transmit it to the AP offices in New York Rockefeller Center via the The box scores are not checked and just rebroadcasted over AP's news delivery If there are corrections those are issued It is the person sitting in front of a laptop at Shea or whereever whose fault that NOTE The AP puts out boxscores in three different formats with the one you see in most newspapers being the first one Not totally For the past year or two the AP has been getting box scores from STATS The AP representative in the press box is actually a STATS reporter dollars a game but free And anybody can do The box is downloaded to STATS in Chicago some quick error checking is done and then STATS sends it to the I'm not sure where the appreveiations come in I don't think it is at STATS' It may just be a space correction by the AP sports editor that While I'm mentioning STATS reporters they are always looking for new Especially if you live in Cleveland or Pittsburgh you're road to getting into the press box may be real For more info call STATS and ask about the reporter It's a fun way to get paid for watching baseball End of public service Last week they were in Maybe the AP person in Denver did this remember they just started with MLB out there Check tomorrow's paper and see if the person who is doing it from Shea does the same Noel Rappin